{"task_name": "gemini-voyager-task-64c72f", "session_id": "64c72f02-bd94-45d3-9334-74fbb19bdba7", "schema_version": "1.1", "repo_url": "https://github.com/Nagi-ovo/gemini-voyager", "base_commit": "b44f33836f1d53cdb3e6dab5cc2c92d84ab9f13a", "replay_status": "ok", "total_replay_warnings": 5, "turn": 0, "user_message": "现在鼠标放在这个时间线上的节点的时候，这个节点会一直抽搐，这是为什么呢？\n\n它有概率在点击之后是不会触发的，很奇怪。", "user_message_chars": 58, "msg_range": [0, 141], "agent_text": "Let me look at the timeline code to understand the twitching and click issues.\n\nLet me look at the specific CSS and hover handling code in detail.\n\nNow I understand the problem. Let me read the full `updateVirtualRangeAndRender` else branch closely.\n\nI've identified the root cause. Here's what's happening:\n\n**Root cause**: `recalculateAndRenderMarkers()` removes **all** dot elements from the DOM and recreates them from scratch every time it runs. This is triggered by a `MutationObserver` watching Gemini's conversation area (debounced to 200ms). Any DOM mutation in Gemini's UI causes all timeline dots to be destroyed and rebuilt.\n\nWhen hovering over a dot:\n1. A Gemini DOM mutation triggers `debouncedRecalc` (200ms debounce)\n2. All dots are removed from DOM (line 1272-1274)\n3. New dots are created at the same positions\n4. But the browser doesn't fire `mouseover` on the new dot until the mouse moves\n5. The dot visually disappears and reappears → **twitching**\n6. If a click lands during the removal window → **click misses**\n\nThe fix: **reuse existing dot elements by turn ID** during recalculation instead of destroying and recreating them all.\n\nNow add orphan cleanup after marker construction, before `this.markersVersion++`:\n\nNow fix the `updateVirtualRangeAndRender` else branch to preserve dots owned by in-range markers:\n\nAlso update `aria-label` and `summary` when reusing dots (the existing update branch doesn't refresh the label):\n\nNow let me verify the changes and run the build:\n\nNo new errors. Let me run the tests and build:\n\nAll 647 tests pass. Now build:\n\nTypecheck, lint, tests, and build all pass. Let me verify the changes look correct:\n\nThe fix is clean. Here's a summary of what was changed and why:\n\n## Problem\n\n`recalculateAndRenderMarkers()` was destroying **all** timeline dot DOM elements and recreating them from scratch every ~200ms (triggered by Gemini's background DOM mutations via MutationObserver). This caused:\n\n1. **Twitching**: The dot visually disappears and reappears as it's removed and recreated. The hover `::after` scale transition (0.15s) makes this visible as jitter.\n2. **Unreliable clicks**: If a click lands during the ~frame gap between dot removal and recreation, `e.target.closest('.timeline-dot')` returns null and the click is silently ignored.\n\n## Fix (3 changes in `manager.ts`)\n\n1. **`recalculateAndRenderMarkers`**: Instead of removing all dots upfront, build a `Map<turnId, DotElement>` from old markers. New markers with matching turn IDs carry over the existing DOM element. Only orphaned dots (turn IDs that no longer exist) are removed.\n\n2. **`updateVirtualRangeAndRender` else branch**: When `visibleRange` is reset, only remove dots not owned by in-range markers (instead of blanket-removing all `.timeline-dot` elements).\n\n3. **Dot update branch**: Added `aria-label` update when reusing dots, so tooltip text stays fresh if the turn summary changed.", "agent_thinking_chars": 0, "ops": [{"kind": "other", "tool": "Agent", "target": "", "detail": ""}, {"kind": "search", "tool": "Grep", "target": "timeline-dot.*hover|\\.timeline-dot:hover", "detail": "/Users/jessezhang/Desktop/Coding/side-projects/gemini-voyager/public/contentStyle.css"}, {"kind": "read", "tool": "Read", "target": "/Users/jessezhang/Desktop/Coding/side-projects/gemini-voyager/src/pages/content/timeline/manager.ts", "detail": ""}, {"kind": "search", "tool": "Grep", "target": "\\.timeline-dot::after", "detail": "/Users/jessezhang/Desktop/Coding/side-projec